1. Define a Problem:

I love the WNBA! There is a lot of analysis done on the men's game, but the women's game deserves as much attention. I want to predict which team statistics(shooting percentages, rebounds, turnovers etc.) most strongly influence winning in the WNBA and find out the key predictors of winning. I also want to explore whether certain teams rely more on offense/defense to win games.

2. Determine the population:

The population is box score statistics from WNBA games played over several seasons. The box score statistics usually includes Team name, opponent, points, rebounds, turnovers and other performance metrics. Each game is treated as a single observation

3.Identify Variable(s)

i) Independent Variables: Points, Turnovers, Rebounds, Steals, Blocks, Field goals, 3 Pointers, Free throws, Personal Fouls.

ii) Dependent Variable: Game outcome (Win/Loss)

iii) Confounder Variable: Player availablity due to injuries and roster changes (missing of an important player), and Inconsistency in game officiating (increase in free throws etc.) can affect game outcomes.

4. Formulate a Hypothesis:

If a team's shooting efficiency (field goal percentage or three point percentage) increases, then the team tends to score more points and win more games.

5. Develop a detailed plan for data collection

To ensure representativeness when using a sample, I will include data from multiple seasons rather than just a single year. I will ensure all WNBA teams are represented in the sample which helps avoid bias towards a particular team.

6. Choose a Dataset:

I find this dataset interesting because it provides a comprehensive view of the wnba games including the game information, team performance stats for both the teams and advanced game metrics. This dataset contains:

  1. Season - the year in which the game was played
  2. Team - Name of the team whose stats are reported
  3. G# - game number for that team
  4. Date
  5. Home - if it is a home game (1) or away game (0)
  6. Opp - Opponent team
  7. W/L - Win or Loss

Team performance stats:

  1. Tm_pts - points scored by the team
  2. Tm_FG - Field goals (any shot other than a free throw) made by the team
  3. Tm_FGA - Field goals attempted by the team
  4. Tm_FG% - Field goal percentage
  5. Tm_3P - Three point Field goals made by the team
  6. Tm_3PA - Three point Field goals attempted by the team
  7. Tm_3PA% - Three point percentage
  8. Tm_FT - Free throws made
  9. Tm_FTA - Free throws attempted
  10. Tm_FT% - Free throw percentage
  11. Tm_ORB - Offensive Rebounds
  12. Tm_TRB - Total Rebounds
  13. Tm_AST - Assists
  14. Tm_STL - Steals
  15. Tm_BLK - blocks
  16. Tm_TOV - turnovers
  17. Tm_PF - Personal fouls committed

Opponent Stats:

  1. Opp_pts - points scored by the opponent
  2. Opp_FG - Field goals (any shot other than a free throw) made by the opponent
  3. Opp_FGA - Field goals attempted by the opponent
  4. Opp_FG% - Field goal percentage
  5. Opp_3P - Three point Field goals made by the opponent
  6. Opp_3PA - Three point Field goals attempted by the opponent
  7. Opp_3PA% - Three point percentage
  8. Opp_FT - Free throws made
  9. Opp_FTA - Free throws attempted
  10. Opp_FT% - Free throw percentage
  11. Opp_ORB - Offensive Rebounds
  12. Opp_TRB - Total Rebounds
  13. Opp_AST - Assists
  14. Opp_STL - Steals
  15. Opp_BLK - blocks
  16. Opp_TOV - turnovers
  17. Opp_PF - Personal fouls committed

Advanced Game Metrics:

  1. win_margin - the difference in the points scored (Tm_pts - Opp_pts)
  2. Tm_poss - Estimated possessions by the team
  3. Opp_poss - Estimated possessions by the opponent
  4. Tm_off_rating - offensive rating (points per 100 possession by the team)
  5. Tm_def_rating - defensive rating (points allowed per 100 possession by the team)
  6. Tm_tov_rate - Team turnover rate (turnovers per possession)
  7. Opp_tov_rate - Opponent turnover rate (turnovers per possession)

I downloaded this dataset from kaggle (Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/natoshakennebrew/wnba-gamelogs-2015-2024) and will be using the file "wnba_gamelogs_2015_2025.csv" for this project. This dataset covers regular season gamelogs from 2015 to 2025.

From 2015 - 2024, the WNBA had 12 teams and in 2025, the league expanded to 13 teams. During the seasons 2015 - 2019, each team played 34 regular season games and in 2020, they played 22 games. In 2021, teams played 32 games and followed by an increase to 36 games in 2022. The schedule expanded to 40 games per team in 2023 and 2024 and in 2025, each team played 44.

2. Special needs for your project?

The dataset used in this project is WNBA Game Logs (2015 - 2024) which contains detailed box score data for every team in each game from 2015 - 2024. It includes performance statistics such as rebounds, steals, blocks, field goals as well as advanced statistics like turnover rates.Each row includes both team level and opponent level statistics for comparitive work, without requiring additonal sources.

Since this dataset is comprehensive and contains all the necessary information, there is no immediate need to merge it with additional datasets.

3. Finding potential issues:

  1. Checking for duplicates: Each row represents a team's performance in a game. So, potential duplicates would appear if a team's game is recorded more than once.

  2. Missing or Null values: Certain metrics such as the Opp_Tov_rate (Opponent turnover rate), Shooting percentages (Team's 3 point%) may be missing due to calculation issues. For example, if a team made zero attempts, their shooting percentage would be undefined. Hence, such cases should be handled with care, they can either be recalculated or left as is if the missingness is meaningful.

  3. Type Consistency: The date column should be in proper datetime format. Numeric performance metrics (eg: assists, blocks etc.) should be integers or floats. The categorical columns (Team name etc.) should be strings / categorical.

  4. Misspellings/ Mistypings: Potential misspellings could be in team name abbreviations. For eg: a team like NYL (New York Liberty) should always appear with the same abbreviation, not as NY or N.Y

  5. Outliers: Outliers in sports data can indicate either a data entry error or an exceptional performance (eg: an unusually high number of blocks). So, outliers should be handled with care and can be detected using Z-scores or by visualizing with boxplots.

  6. Other Possible issues:

  • A team labeled 'W' should have a higher score than its opponent
  • Calculated metrics (like Tm_3P%) should be consistent with their raw components (eg:Tm_3P and Tm_3PA)

4. Reorganization:

The column "G#" can be renamed to "Game_no" and 'W/L' can be renamed to 'Win_Loss'

5. Detailed Plan for Cleaning:

  1. Duplicates: the duplicates found using df.duplicated(). Removed them using df.drop_duplicates()

  2. 'Opp_tov_rate' had all values as 1, which was incorrect. Recalculated using existed columns. Shooting percentages with zero attempts set to 0.

  3. Converted 'Date' column to datetime using pd.to_datetime().

  4. Checked if all the team names are consistent, using df["Team"].unique() and df["Team"].value_counts()

  5. Identified outliers in numeric columns using Z-score. For example, 'Tm_BLK' had an outlier, which was verified as genuine and retained. Also, visualized as boxplots.

  6. Verified that the team labeled 'W' has more points than its opponents. Recalculated derived metrics from its raw components. For eg: df["Tm_3P%"] = (df["Tm_3P"] / df["Tm_3PA"])

How Tov_rate is calculated?

It uses the formula: TOV % = TOV / Possessions (from: https://www.nbastuffer.com/analytics101/turnover-ratio/)

where [Possessions=FGA+0.44FTAORB+TOV] (from: https://www.nbastuffer.com/analytics101/possession/)

In[]:
# we check how Tm_tov_rate is calculated
calc_Tm_tov_rate = df["Tm_TOV"] / (
    df["Tm_FGA"] + 0.44 * df["Tm_FTA"] - df["Tm_ORB"] + df["Tm_TOV"]
)

Detecting Outliers:

First, Z-score function is imported. 'numeric_cols' contains performance metrics for both the team and opponent. We apply zscore() to every numeric column and this creates a new dataframe 'z_score' of the same shape, with each value replaced by its z-score. If the absolute z-score is greater than 3, it is considered as a potential outlier.

The number of outliers in each column is counted and sorted based on the number of outliers.

In[]:
from scipy.stats import zscore
numeric_cols = ['Tm_Pts',
       'Opp_Pts', 'Tm_FG', 'Tm_FGA', 'Tm_FG%', 'Tm_3P', 'Tm_3PA', 'Tm_3P%',
       'Tm_FT', 'Tm_FTA', 'Tm_FT%', 'Tm_ORB', 'Tm_TRB', 'Tm_AST', 'Tm_STL',
       'Tm_BLK', 'Tm_TOV', 'Tm_PF', 'Opp_FG', 'Opp_FGA', 'Opp_FG%', 'Opp_3P',
       'Opp_3PA', 'Opp_3P%', 'Opp_FT', 'Opp_FTA', 'Opp_FT%', 'Opp_ORB',
       'Opp_TRB', 'Opp_AST', 'Opp_STL', 'Opp_BLK', 'Opp_TOV', 'Opp_PF',
       'win_margin', 'Tm_poss', 'Opp_poss', 'Tm_off_rating', 'Tm_def_rating',
       'Tm_tov_rate', 'Opp_tov_rate']

z_score = df[numeric_cols].apply(zscore)
outliers = (z_score.abs() > 3)
outlier_counts = outliers.sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
print("outliers by column",outlier_counts)

From the results:

The z score analysis identified several potential outliers. However, after examining the descriptive statistics and considering the context of basketball games, the values likely represent genuine extreme performances rather than data entry errors.

For example: There are two games where Teams' recorded 14 blocks, we can even verify it from the basketball reference site offical box scores, for row 162 (LAS VS SAS on 23/08/2015)-https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/boxscores/201508230SAS.html and for row 1116(ATL VS LVA on 08/07/2018) - https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/boxscores/201808070ATL.html

Therefore, instead of removing these values, we retain them as valid observations as they capture natural variability in team performance.

ii) Variables and their units:

  1. Season - the year in which the game was played
  2. Team - Name of the team whose stats are reported
  3. G# - game number for that team
  4. Date
  5. Home - if it is a home game (1) or away game (0) - (binary categorical variable)
  6. Opp - Opponent team
  7. Win_Loss - Win or Loss

Team performance stats:

  1. Tm_pts - points scored by the team, units are measured
  2. Tm_FG - Field goals (any shot other than a free throw) made by the team
  3. Tm_FGA - Field goals attempted by the team
  4. Tm_FG% - Field goal percentage
  5. Tm_3P - Three point Field goals made by the team
  6. Tm_3PA - Three point Field goals attempted by the team
  7. Tm_3PA% - Three point percentage
  8. Tm_FT - Free throws made
  9. Tm_FTA - Free throws attempted
  10. Tm_FT% - Free throw percentage
  11. Tm_ORB - Offensive Rebounds
  12. Tm_TRB - Total Rebounds
  13. Tm_AST - Assists
  14. Tm_STL - Steals
  15. Tm_BLK - blocks
  16. Tm_TOV - turnovers
  17. Tm_PF - Personal fouls committed

Opponent Stats:

  1. Opp_pts - points scored by the opponent
  2. Opp_FG - Field goals (any shot other than a free throw) made by the opponent
  3. Opp_FGA - Field goals attempted by the opponent
  4. Opp_FG% - Field goal percentage
  5. Opp_3P - Three point Field goals made by the opponent
  6. Opp_3PA - Three point Field goals attempted by the opponent
  7. Opp_3PA% - Three point percentage
  8. Opp_FT - Free throws made
  9. Opp_FTA - Free throws attempted
  10. Opp_FT% - Free throw percentage
  11. Opp_ORB - Offensive Rebounds
  12. Opp_TRB - Total Rebounds
  13. Opp_AST - Assists
  14. Opp_STL - Steals
  15. Opp_BLK - blocks
  16. Opp_TOV - turnovers
  17. Opp_PF - Personal fouls committed

Advanced Game Metrics:

  1. win_margin - the difference in the points scored (Tm_pts - Opp_pts)
  2. Tm_poss - Estimated possessions by the team
  3. Opp_poss - Estimated possessions by the opponent
  4. Tm_off_rating - offensive rating (points per 100 possession by the team)
  5. Tm_def_rating - defensive rating (points allowed per 100 possession by the team)
  6. Tm_tov_rate - Team turnover rate (turnovers per possession)
  7. Opp_tov_rate - Opponent turnover rate (turnovers per possession)

Shooting percentages - Opp_FG%, Opp_3P%, Opp_FT%, Tm_FG%, Tm_3P%, Tm_FT% Tm_tov_rate, Opp_tov_rate are measured as fractions.

Derived metrics - Tm_off_rating and Tm_def_rating are counts derived from game flow formulas.

Counts - Many variables are simple counts during the game including, (team and opponent)- points, steal, blocks, rebounds, 3P,3PA, free throws, free throw attempts, assists, turnovers, personal fouls.

  1. Identifying outliers, missing data, summary statistics, distribution and frequency of the variables values:

The variables are categorized as categorical, numerical and date.

From the descriptive statistics below:

i) All variables have 4513 records and there are no missing values found.

ii) Outliers: Tm_pts and Opp_pts have a few high scoring games above the 75th percentile (max = 118). Shooting stats such as Tm_FT and Tm_FGA show extreme values which reflect high scoring and low scoring games. These outliers are reasonable in the context of a basketball game. Unusually high points, field goals, possesions can occur during some matches (as discussed in project-2).

iii) Histograms reveal that most variables have symmetric distribution with moderate spread. Extreme values are also visible but rare, they align with expected basketball performance variance.

Opponent team - Most teams appear the same number of times, except for TUL and SAS which are no longer in the league.

Win_Loss - 2283 Wins and 2229 losses.

Seasons from 2016 - 2019, have many more games than 2020 season which is likely due to COVID 19 bubble season. There is a sharp increase again in the later seasons.

Hypothesis - If a team's shooting efficiency (field goal percentage or three point percentage) increases, then the team tends to score more points and win more games.

Independent variables - Tm_FG%, Tm_3P%, TmFT%,Tm_off_rating, Tm_def_rating, Tm_TOV, Tm_AST, Tm_STL,Tm_BLK,Tm_PF,Tm_poss,Tm_TOV_rate, Opp_FG%, Opp_3P%, Opp_FT%,Opp_off_rating, Opp_def_rating, Opp_TOV, Opp_AST, Opp_STL,Opp_BLK,Opp_PF,Opp_poss,Opp_TOV_rate

These variables describe the outcome of the game. They are determined after all the actions have occured. For eg: A team's higher FG% and low turnover rate may contribute to a win or higher positive win_margin.

Simpson's Paradox: A team may have lower success rates in 2P%(2-point percentage) and 3P% (3 point percentage)but have a higher overall Field goal percentage (FG%).

In basketball, a common subgroup is 'shot type', specifically 2-point versus 3-point shots because teams attempt different proportions of these shots and 2-point shots are easier to make than 3-point shots.

I first calculated the number of 2-point shots mad and attempted for each game by subtracting the 3-point shots from the toal field goals and total field goal attempts. I aggregated these numbers across all games in a season for each team to obtrain the season totals for 2 point scored and attempts, 3-point scored and attempts. Using these totals, I calculated the season level shooting percentages for 2-pointers and 3-pointers and overall field-goals. So, the percentages are correctly weighted by the number of attempts.

By examining all pairs of teams, within each season to identify cases where Team A had lower 2P% and 3P% than Team B but a higher overall FG%. These pairs are examples of Simpson's paradox.

For example: SEA is better than MIN in both 2-point and 3-point shooting percentages. But the overall FG% for MIN is higher than SEA.

Reason: MIN may have scored easier 2-point shots which resulted in a high FG%. Even though, SEA was more accurate with the shot-type, they may have attempted more 3 pointers (difficult to score) which lowered their combined FG%

Reference: https://www.mickmel.com/simpsons-paradox-can-make-sports-stats-look-weird/

https://medium.com/@vplevris/simpsons-paradox-in-sports-when-better-every-season-still-means-worse-overall-c0508c2a96e6

import itertools
def find_simpsons_paradox(season_totals):
    paradox_pairs = []

    for season in season_totals['Season'].unique():
        season_df = season_totals[season_totals['Season'] == season]


        for team_a, team_b in itertools.combinations(season_df['Team'], 2):
            a = season_df[season_df['Team'] == team_a].iloc[0]
            b = season_df[season_df['Team'] == team_b].iloc[0]


            if (a['Tm_2P%'] < b['Tm_2P%']) and (a['Tm_3P%'] < b['Tm_3P%']) and (a['Tm_FG%'] > b['Tm_FG%']):
                paradox_pairs.append({
                    'Season': season,
                    'Team A': team_a,
                    'Team B': team_b,
                    'Team A 2P%': a['Tm_2P%'],
                    'Team B 2P%': b['Tm_2P%'],
                    'Team A 3P%': a['Tm_3P%'],
                    'Team B 3P%': b['Tm_3P%'],
                    'Team A FG%': a['Tm_FG%'],
                    'Team B FG%': b['Tm_FG%']
                })

    return pd.DataFrame(paradox_pairs)


paradox_df = find_simpsons_paradox(season_totals)

Principal Component Analysis:

The cleaned dataset initially had 27 features after removing identifiers and raw counts. Many of these features are highly correlated in basketball, in this context, this can lead to multicollinearity, where two or more independent variables have a high correlation with one another.

To address this, I used PCA to reduce multicollinearity and capture most of the dataset's variance with fewer dimensions. PCA transformed 27 features into 17 features while retaining 95% of the total variance. PCA helps the model to focus on the major patterns that contribute to winning

Features come from different statistical categories such as shooting percentages, rebounding counts, possession metrics and defensive statistics. These features exist on very different scales. StandardScaler is used which standardizes every feature to have a mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1. It uses z-score standardization.

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.preprocessing.StandardScaler.html

Two feature selection methods were applied to the dataset: a filter method (ANOVA F-test) and a wrapper method (forward selection using KNN). Both the methods reduced the features down to 15. The difference lies in which features were chosen:

The filter method selects features based on their individual statistical correlation with the target, ignoring interactions between the features. The wrapper method evaluates how subsets of features perform together in the model.

The benefit of reducing dimensionality is that it simplifies the dataset by keeping only the most important features. This makes models faster to train, reduces noise and errors and less likely to overfit.

  1. What algorithm will you use?

For this project, a decision tree classifier will be used as a baseline model. A decision tree is appropriate because it can model non-linear relationships between in-game statistics and target outcomes.

What assumptions does this algorithm make?

Decision Trees do not assume that the features follow any specific distribution, they do not require features to be independent and they can handle moderate outliers.

In this dataset, many of the basketball statistics are correlated, eg: FGA relates to points and possesions, so using a model that is robust to correlation is better.

Decision Tree classifier help to model realtionships between shooting efficienty, turnovers, rebounding and defensive metrics.

Is this algorithm known to be prone to any issues that you should watch out for? Are there well-known mitigations you should use?

Decision Trees are susceptible to overfitting, especially when the tree grows too deep and begins to memorize noise in the training data. To address this risk, the model was intentionally constrained using parameters such as max_depth = 6, min_samples_leaf = 5 and min_samples_split = 10.(To optimize this, grid search will be applied to test a range of values).

Limiting the depth of the tree prevents it from creating overly complex rules that apply only to a small subset of games. Similarly, requiring a minimum number of samples per leaf and split avoids divisions that are too specific to rare game outcomes.

Explain why you think this algorithm is a good candidate for the ML task

Decision Tree classifier is a good candidate for this task because it can capture non - linear relationships and handle interactions between features which are common in baskeball statistics. For example, a team's chance of winning depends not only on shooting efficiency but also on how turnovers, rebounds and assists interact in a game. A decision tree works by recursively splitting the data based on feature thresholds, forming regions where the target variable is more homogeneous. It is flexible with scaling and can be controlled with hyperparamers like max_depth and min_sample_leaf

  1. What are the hyperparameters for your algorithm and how will you choose/tune them?

Hyperparameters for decision tree classifier:

  1. max_depth = the maximum depth of the tree, how many layers of splits it can make.

  2. min_samples_leaf = the minimum number of samples required to be in a leaf node

  3. min_samples_split = the minimum number of samples needed for a node to be considered for a split

  4. criterion = 'gini'. The function used to measure the quality of the split.

  1. Are there any post processing techniques you may need to apply?

Decision trees can overfit if allowed to grow too deep, so post pruning is sometimes used to simplify a fully grown tree. In this project, the tree's complexity is controlled during training, by setting the pre-pruning hyperparameters (max_depth, min_samples_leaf, min_samples_split), the tree's complexity is controlled during training, so no additional post-processing is required.

Grid search is used to tune the hyperparameters of a decision tree classifier. First, a set of possible values is defined for max_depth, min_samples_leaf and min_samples_split. The GridSearchCV function then systematically tries all combinations with R^2 metric. The tree is trained multiple times on different subsets of training data and the average is recorded. Finally grid.best_params_ and grid.best_score_ return the combination of hyperparameters that gave the highest cross-validated R^2.

Project-5

Previously, PCA, filter methods and a single decision tree classifier were applied for feature reduction and prediction. PCA was not suitable because it combines original features into abstract components, which makes it difficult to interpret the influence of game statistics.

The original dataset contained identifiers, redundant statistics, and outcome - derived variables. Includeing all features would introduce data leakage and reduced interpretability. Therefore, Identifiers such as Season, Team, Opponent, Date and Game Number were excluded because they do not describe in-game performance and may reduce generalizability. Outcome-related variables such as Team points, Opponent Points, Win Margin were removed to prevent data leakage, Raw box-score counts (field goals made and attempted) were exluded when corresponding efficiency metrics were available, as percentages better capture performance while reducing redundancy. Advanced metrics such as ratings, possessions and turnover rates were also excluded because they are computed from fundamental statistics already present in the dataset.

The final feature set consisted of 17 fundamental offensive and defensive statistics including shooting efficiency, rebounding, turnovers, fould, defensive actions for both teams.

Key Basketball performance features selected using domain knowledge are defined as the input variables, and the game outcome is defined as the target variable.

RFECV (Recursive Feature Elimination with Cross-Validation) is a model-based feature selection technique that iteratively removes less important features while evaluating model performance using cross validation

In[]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import RFECV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

estimator = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear',random_state =42, max_iter=1000)

rfecv = RFECV(estimator = estimator, step = 1, cv = StratifiedKFold(5), scoring = 'accuracy')

rfecv.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

print(f"\n optimal number of features found by RFECV: {rfecv.n_features_}")

print(X.columns[rfecv.support_].tolist())

RFECV was applied using logistic regression as the base model and accuracy as the scoring metric. Conceptually, RFECV removes the least important feature at each step and checks whether cross-validated performance improves. If removing a feature would reduce performance, it is retained.

In this case, all 17 features were retained because logistic regression uses feature coefficients to assess importance, and RFECV removes only features whose exclusion does not reduce cross-validated accuracy. All selected features contributed to maintaining optimal performance.

The dataset is reduced to the subset of features selected by RFECV. These features are then standardized again to ensure consistent scaling before training.

Metrics:

Accuracy: measures the overall proportion of games correctly predicted as wins or losses.

Precision: measures the proportion of predicted wins that were actual wins.

Recall: measures the proportion of actual wins correctly predicted.

F1-Score: combines precision and recall into a single measure and provides a balanced view of the model's ability to correctly identify wins.

Confusion Matrix: shows the counts of true positives (games that were actually wins and predicted as wins), true negatives (games that were losses and predicted as losses), false positives(games that were losses but predicted as wins) and false negatives(games that were wins but predicted as losses). This highlights whether the model is consistently predicting wins or losses correctly.

Inference from results:

The logistic regression model achieved train accuracy is 0.941 and test accuracy is 0.942. Precision and recall and F1-scores are all 0.94. The confusion matrix confirms few, evenly distributed misclassifications. These results support the hypothesis that the selected performance features effectively capture the factors influencing game outcomes.

The logistic regression model shows identical metrics, which suggested that the model may be overfitting or too confident in its predictions.

L2-regularized logistic regression:

To address potential overfitting in original logistic overfitting, L2-regularized logistic regression is applied

L2 regularization is a technique that penalizes large coefficients in a model by adding the sum of their squares to the loss function. This shrinks the coefficients toward zero without removing any features, which helps the model avoid overfitting and generalize better to unseen data.

In the code below, RFECV with L2 regularized logistic regression selected 17 optimal features. L2 regulatization did not remove any features, showing that none are redundant or irrelevant in the presence of coefficient shrinkage

In[]:

Random Forest Classifier:

The decision tree achieved moderate performance but with several misclassifications, so random forest classifier is implemented next.

Random forest is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees on random subsets of the data and features. Each tree makes a prediction, and the final output is determined by majority voting. This approach reduced overfitting compared and can capture complex, non linear relationships in the data

In the code below, RFECV is run using random forest as the classifier

Insights:

  1. What did you find in terms of your hypothesis?

Hypothesis: Higher shooting efficiency (measured by field goal percentage or 3 Point percentage etc.) is associated with winning games.

Classification models (logistic regression, l2-regularized logistic regression, decision tree and random forest) show that features such as Tm_FG%, Tm_3P%, and defensive/possession metrics (Tm_TRB,Tm_TOV,Opp_TRB,Opp_TOV) are highly informative in distinguishing wins from losses. RFECV confirms that shooting efficiency and certain defensive metrics are the strongest predictors. This supports the hypothesis: games won are strongly associated with higher shooting efficiency and good defensive control.

  1. Any previous assumptions that you had to adjust, or proved wrong?

Originally, only team shooting efficiency was assumed to matter. The analysis shows that opponent statistics and turnovers also significantly influence outcomes. Not all available features contribute equally; a subset of features capture most of the predictive power.

  1. Is the problem different from what you had originally thought?

Initially, the focus was on offense. Results indicate that both offense and defense (defensive statistics such as rebounds, steals and turovers) are critical in determining game outcomes.

  1. Anything you would do differently if you were to do it again?

I would analyze sequences of games to capture momentum or performance trends. Although, I have addressed '3 point scored per game' performance trend from 2015-2025, in the previous section, extending ML models to include temporal patterns could improve predictions.

  1. Are there any policy or other decisions that could be influenced by an analysis like yours?

Coaches can focus on improving shooting efficiency, minimizing turnovers and strengthening defensive play. Teams can prioritize player selection and training based on metrics that truly influence game outcomes.

  1. What ethical concerns should you or someone reading your project consider?

Predictive models should not be exploited for gambling, which raises legal and ethical concerns.

  1. Final thoughts: Summarize your experience across all 5 projects. What did you learn?

Across the five projects, I learned the complete data science pipeline. Early on, I learned the importance of careful data cleaning and validation, especially recognizing that extreme values in basketball statistics often reflect real performances rather than errors and are worth cross-verifying rather than removing.

The exploratory analysis helped me better understand how different basketball metrics relate to each other, and concepts like correlation and Simpson's paradox showed that performance statistics can be misleading if not analyzed correctly. Moving to machine learning taught me how to properly frame the problem as a classification task, avoid data leakage (box scores are prone to data leakage), and select features that actually matter. I also learned that not every method works for every problem: experimenting with PCA showed me why dimensionality reduction can sometimes hurt performance, in this case, the original features are already meaningful and interpretable for classification.

One of the biggest takeaways was realizing that winning is not driven by offense alone, defense stats like turnovers and opponent performance are just as important. What started as a simple question about whether shooting efficiency leads to winning in the WNBA evolved into an analysis of how offense, defense, and opponent behavior interact.
